    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i checked the min/max logs and they actually look fine, it's more like the actual distribution of the features is behaving weirdly. and i'm also seeing some strange patterns in the clustering results where certain groups of data points are being flagged as \"unstable\" or \"highly volatile\" even when they should be uniform. is there any reason a standard scaler would cause that kind of sudden shift in group cohesion?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "There could be several reasons for the observed cluster volatility. A standard scaler should not directly affect group cohesion unless the features being scaled have significant changes in means or variances across batches. If the clustering results are erratic, it may be due to the chosen features themselves, how the features are scaled, or potentially undiscovered underlying patterns within the data such as outliers. Consider using a different scaling method like Min-Max Normalization which scales according to the range of the data within the features rather than their distribution. Also, verify that your clustering algorithm is homogeneous across model iterations and check if there are anomalies in your dataset that might lead to \"highly volatile\" groupings. It could be beneficial to visualize the distribution of your features before and after scaling for each batch to identify any alterations. Additionally, experiment with various clustering algorithms to check if the instability persists, which might suggest inherent properties of the data rather than an issue with preprocessing.",
